@REM KEY 0 0 "Plotter" "Description of the toolbar"
@{U}5.3) Description of the toolbar@{UU}

   Each plotter window has a toolbar at the top.

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}zoom in@{UB} - Magnifies the current view by 25%.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}zoom out@{UB} - Shrinks the current view to 80%.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}move left@{UB} - Move the visible area 50% to the left.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}move right@{UB} - Move the visible area 50% to the right.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}move up@{UB} - Move the visible area 50% up.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}move down@{UB} - Move the visible area 50% down.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}settings@{UB} - Open the settings window.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlotterSettings"
@TITLE "The settings window"
@NEXT "PlotterAnim"
@PREV "PlotterToolbar"
@TOC "Plotter"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------- The settings window -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Plotter" "The settings window"
@{U}5.4) The settings window@{UU}

   The settings window offers a lot of  attributes to adjust the plot to  your
requirements.

   The window is divided into five sections:

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Range@{UB}
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Axis@{UB}
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Functions@{UB}
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Animation@{UB}
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Color@{UB}

   When the settings window is opened, the current settings are backed up.  By
hitting @{B}Use@{UB} the settings are applied to the plotter and the settings window is
closed. @{B}Update@{UB} just applies the settings, but the settings window remains open
and the backed up settings are not changed. @{B}Cancel@{UB} closes the settings  window
and restored the backed up settings.

   The following functions are available in the menu:

 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Restore@{UB} - Restore the settings to the state when the settings window was
   opened.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Load@{UB} - Load the settings from a file.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Save@{UB} - Save the settings to a file.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Save as...@{UB} - Request a filename and save the settings to this file.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}Close@{UB} - Same as hitting the @{B}Cancel@{UB} button.

@{U}Range@{UU}

   Here you  can specify  the visible  area.  If @{B}auto  scale@{UB} is  enabled,  the
Y-range is adjusted to the minimum  and maximum of the displayed functions  in
the given X-range.

@{U}Axis@{UU}

   This section specifies the design of the X- and Y-axis.

 @{B}À@{UB} The @{B}type@{UB} determines, whether you  want the axis to  be drawn as a  cross
   and/or as a box around the area. The cross is centered to the origin, if
   it is visible.
 @{B}À@{UB} With the @{B}axis mode@{UB} gadget, you can select for the X- and Y-axis, whether
   it should be drawn with a linear or logarithmic scale.
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}big marks@{UB} and @{B}small marks@{UB} define the distances between the marks on each
   axis. Both types of marks can be disabled using the checkmark gadget. If
   the axis has  a logarithmic  scale, this  distance refers  to the  first
   decade (1...10). A value of  5 means that marks  are drawn at the  posi-
   tions ...0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 500,...
 @{B}À@{UB} @{B}raster 1@{UB} and  @{B}raster 2@{UB} define  the distance between  the horizontal  and
   vertical raster lines. There are  two different raster, each one  having
   it's own color. Both types of raster can be disabled using the checkmark
   gadget. Just like the marks, on a logarithmic scale the distance  refers
   to the first decade.
 @{B}À@{UB} The distance between two numbers is  adjusted by @{B}labels@{UB}. If the  numbers
   get too tight, some of them are automatically left out to avoid overlap-
   ping.

@{U}Functions@{UU}

   Each function that is displayed in  the plotter window can have some  local
settings:

 @{B}À@{UB} The function can  have it's  own X-range. If  you enable  @{B}own range@{UB}  the
   graph of the function is limited to this range.
 @{B}À@{UB} Especially when you  display an  animated plot, the  calculation of  the
   function's value table might take some time. You can reduce this time by
   reducing the @{B}precision@{UB}.  A maximal precision  means that the  function's
   value is calculated for every pixel of the X-range, with minimal  preci-
   sion only every 16th value is calculated.
 @{B}À@{UB} And finally each function graph can have it's own @{B}color@{UB}.

@{U}Animation@{UU}

   This section is only available, if the plotter is opened in animation mode.
Every  function  has  than  a   second  variable  (that  you  specified   with
@{"plot_addfunc()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-PLOT-ADDFUNC"}). Here you specify the @{B}minimum@{UB} and @{B}maximum@{UB} value of the  second
variable and the  @{B}step size@{UB} by  which it is  incremented with every  animation
frame.

@{U}Color@{UU}

   Here you adjust the colors of the difference components of the plot.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlotterAnim"
@TITLE "Animated plots"
@PREV "PlotterSettings"
@TOC "Plotter"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual -------------------------------------------- Animated plots -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Plotter" "Animated plots"
@{U}5.5) Animated plots@{UU}

   If you opened an animated plotter, a small window called @{B}Animation  control@{UB}
is opened and the @{B}Animation@{UB} section of the settings window is enabled.

   The @{B}Animation control@{UB} has five buttons to start and stop the animation. Be-
fore an animation  is started, Laplace  has to calculate  the graphs for  each
frame (doing this  in real-time would  be too slow...).  This calculation  may
take some time. You can speed this up by reducing the @{B}display precision@{UB} of the
function(s), but this reduces the quality of the graph.

   @{B}frames per second@{UB} specifies the speed of the animation. Up to 50 frames per
second can be requested, but the  real speed, which is display below,  depends
on the complexity and size of the graph and the speed of you computer.

   At the bottom of the control window is the current value of the second  pa-
rameter. You can  change it to  display single frames,  without rendering  the
whole animation.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
